<Layout title="Section 6 – Nutrition & Tubes">
  <h1>Section 6: Nutrition &amp; Tubes</h1>
  <p><em>Competency 7093.4.6 – Performs Nutritional Support Interventions</em></p>
  <p>
    Describe nursing interventions for patients with special nutritional needs and TPN
    nutrition, including enteral tube feedings and nasogastric tube insertion.
  </p>

  <h2 id="nutritional-assessment">Nutritional Assessment</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Review dietary history, weight changes, BMI, laboratory values (albumin, prealbumin, transferrin).</li>
    <li>Assess for dysphagia (swallowing difficulty) — refer to speech-language pathology as indicated.</li>
    <li>Screen using validated tools (e.g., MNA for older adults, NRS-2002 for hospitalized patients).</li>
    <li>Identify risk factors: NPO status, illness-related anorexia, malabsorption, wounds, surgery.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="aspiration">Aspiration Precautions</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Elevate HOB to ≥ 30–45° during and for 30–60 minutes after meals or tube feedings.</li>
    <li>Offer thickened liquids per speech therapy recommendation (IDDSI framework).</li>
    <li>Encourage small, frequent meals; supervise meals for high-risk patients.</li>
    <li>Keep suction equipment at bedside for patients with high aspiration risk.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="warning">
    <strong>⚠️ Aspiration Risk</strong>
    Signs of aspiration include coughing/choking during eating, wet or gurgly voice quality,
    recurrent pneumonia, and oxygen desaturation during meals.
  </div>

  <h2 id="intake-output">Intake &amp; Output (I&amp;O)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Record all fluid intake: oral, IV, tube feeding, irrigation fluids.</li>
    <li>Record all output: urine, emesis, wound drainage, NG tube drainage, ostomy output, stool.</li>
    <li>Normal urine output: ≥ 0.5 mL/kg/hr; report output &lt; 30 mL/hr for &gt; 2 hours.</li>
    <li>Convert volumes to mL; 1 oz = 30 mL; 1 cup = 240 mL.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="ng-tube">Nasogastric (NG) Tube</h2>
  <h3>Indications</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Enteral feeding when oral intake is contraindicated or insufficient</li>
    <li>Gastric decompression (e.g., bowel obstruction, post-op ileus)</li>
    <li>Medication administration</li>
    <li>Gastric lavage</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Insertion Key Points</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Measure from tip of nose to earlobe to xiphoid process (NEX measurement).</li>
    <li>Position patient with HOB elevated 45–90°; have patient flex chin to chest during insertion.</li>
    <li>Verify placement before each use: X-ray is gold standard; check pH of aspirate (&lt; 5.5 confirms gastric placement).</li>
    <li>Never use air bolus or auscultation alone to confirm placement.</li>
    <li>Mark tube at naris and document length.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="enteral">Enteral Tube Feedings</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Check residual volume before bolus feedings; hold if &gt; 250–500 mL (per facility policy).</li>
    <li>Flush tube with 30 mL water before and after feedings and medications.</li>
    <li>Maintain HOB ≥ 30° continuously during and after feedings.</li>
    <li>Monitor for complications: diarrhea, nausea, aspiration, tube displacement, clogging.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="tpn">Total Parenteral Nutrition (TPN)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Administered IV when the GI tract cannot be used (bowel obstruction, severe malabsorption, short bowel syndrome).</li>
    <li>Requires central venous access (PICC or central line).</li>
    <li>Monitor blood glucose closely — TPN can cause hyperglycemia.</li>
    <li>Never abruptly discontinue TPN — taper to prevent rebound hypoglycemia.</li>
    <li>Change tubing every 24 hours; inspect insertion site for infection.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="tip">
    <strong>💡 Key Principle</strong>
    "If the gut works, use it." Enteral nutrition is preferred over TPN when the GI tract is functional
    because it maintains gut integrity, reduces infection risk, and is less costly.
  </div>

